data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current code uses `Assert.IsTrue` for everything, which gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — gives "Expected:3 Actual:5" on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // CollectionAssert for collection-specific checks
    CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));

    // Assert.IsNotNull is clearer intent than Assert.IsTrue(x != null)
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key takeaways:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` or just check exact count | Better failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual; use `Count` property not LINQ `Count()` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent + better message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(items.All(...))` | `CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy(...)` | Tells you *which* element failed |

Also useful from `CollectionAssert`:
- **`Contains(collection, item)`** — membership check
- **`AreEquivalent(expected, actual)`** — same elements, any order
- **`AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — same elements, same order
- **`AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`** — no duplicates
